Table 2
 shows the mechanical properties of neat XNBR latex, XNBR with various ratios of CDs, XNBR with various ratios of GO and XNBR+2CDs with various ratios of GO. The breaking stress value and stress at 100% strain value of XNBR latex increases with increase in CDs concentration upto 2 phr and beyond which it starts to decrease (Table 2). The breaking stress value and stress at 100% strain value of XNBR+2CDs nanocomposite is 220% and 680% higher than the breaking stress value and stress at 100% strain value of neat XNBR latex (Fig. 7
). Strain at break (%) value of XNBR latex has been found to slightly decrease with the incorporation of 2 phr of CDs (Table 2). From our earlier publication, it has been shown that the significant increase in the mechanical properties of XNBR latex by incorporation of 2 phr of CDs (optimum concentration) is ascribed to the excellent dispersion of CDs in XNBR matrix via. covalent conjugation [27]. From Table 2 it is seen that the breaking stress value and stress at 100% strain value of XNBR latex increases with the increase in GO concentration up to 2 vol % beyond which it starts to decrease. Hence, it is clear that 2 vol % of GO has been found to be the optimum concentration for improving the mechanical properties of XNBR latex (Table 2). It should be pointed here that the mechanical properties of XNBR latex containing 2 phr of CDs is higher in comparison to mechanical properties of XNBR containing 2 vol % of GO (Table 2).
